<p>Road contracts mobilise local employment—labourers, pavers, truck drivers—and ripple through bitumen suppliers and quarry logistics. Incumbents trumpet kilometres; challengers highlight stretches left out. Voters often reward visible fixes but punish dust and diversions if projects drag. In an election year, timelines risk political pressure; engineers insist on technically sound curing periods even when campaign clocks tick loudly.</p>

